column1: Revised: Feb 06, 2023         Parker Solar Probe / Sun                    -96
The Parker Solar Probe Mission will use seven Venus gravity assist flybys
over nearly seven years to gradually bring the spacecraft's trajectory closer
to the Sun, which it will orbit at least 24 times with a final solar orbit
The spacecraft will fly through the Sun's outer corona, 5.9 million km from
The orbit will be highly elliptical to minimize the time spent closest
to the Sun, where incident solar radiation will be approximately 520 times
the intensity at Earth and temperatures near 2500 deg. F (1377 C).
Date:           2018-Aug-12 07:31 UTC from NASA Kennedy Space Center
Launch vehicle: Delta IV Heavy with Upper Stage

Barycentric Dynamical Time ("TDB" or T_eph) output was requested. This
continuous coordinate time is equivalent to the relativistic proper time
of a clock at rest in a reference frame co-moving with the solar system
barycenter but outside the system's gravity well. It is the independent
variable in the solar system relativistic equations of motion.
TDB runs at a uniform rate of one SI second per second and is independent
Mixed calendar mode was active such that calendar dates after AD 1582-Oct-15
(if any) are in the modern Gregorian system. Dates prior to 1582-Oct-5 (if any)
are in the Julian calendar system, which is automatically extended for dates
prior to its adoption on 45-Jan-1 BC.  The Julian calendar is useful for
matching historical dates. The Gregorian calendar more accurately corresponds
to the Earth's orbital motion and seasons. A "Gregorian-only" calendar mode is
available if such physical events are the primary interest.
